field_reports.description:
On Monday 15th March, 2021, there were clashes among local communities in one of the fishing villages (Sanyang) in The Gambia. A Senegalese national during a robbery attempt killed a Gambian that eventually made the locals of Sanyang to attack the Senegalese population living in the village. Several people were injured causing displacements among the people. The Gambia Red Cross Society responded during the clashes with First Aid personnel and two ambulances operated by our GPlus Emergency Response Services. Twenty-three (23) injured people recorded. 


As of 17th March 2021, the Senegalese are displaced and being hosted in a very small nursery school in the community of Batokunku. The number registered at the hosting centre has drastically increased and more family members are joining, especially women and children which is overstretching the hosting capacity of the community. GRCS has registered 81 households with a total population of 483 people. The National Society (NS) is providing assistance to such people as stated below.

•	GRCS is providing additional support to the affected population to cover their most urgent needs. This includes the provision of additional: 
o	180 blankets, for the entire affected population;
o	5 packets of soap for laundry and other domestic uses;
o	450 pieces of toilet soap for personal hygiene (bath);
o	600 facemasks to provide protection against COVID-19 and cut the chain of transmission among the population;
o	70 bottles (500ml each) of hand sanitizers distributed targeting households;
o	4 hand wash facilities installed within and outside the premises;
o	20 boxes of assorted clothing;
o	5 big buckets for drinking;

•	The GRCS has also addressed the sanitation concern of the population by ensuring the full maintenance of 5 toilets which were not functioning and in deplorable conditions;
•	Supported the referral of 2 persons to the hospital for medical attention;
•	Provided First Aid service to 5 people at the reception centre;
•	Established WASH and FOOD committees among the population to ensure the maintenance of good health and hygiene status of the people and proper food management;
•	Provided special needs to children, women, and girls - considering their needs (menstrual pads, diapers, laundry buckets, linings/ropes, clips, baby clothing and beddings, among others); 

•	Some specific vulnerabilities that were also identified were:
o	7 pregnant women were reported by household heads;
o	18 breastfeeding women were recorded; 
o	59 children under the age of 5 recorded;
o	Some significant number of minors were also present at the hosting centre;
o	Some woman have health condition (diabetes, hypertension) that require special attention
•	1 person expressed need for RFL; 
•	Majority of the people hosted are fishermen who expressed concerns over the loss of their livelihoods (fishing boats, machines, nets) as a result of them been burnt by the local community
•	Further needs identified by the people were:
o	Overcrowding/congestion at the centre 
o	Kettles 
o	Mats 
o	Detol 
o	Additional buckets needed on the ground for the newly registered families and women.
•	Also, more food and non-food items will be required as households are increasing daily. Health services will also be needed.

•	In terms of scalability, there is high tendency for other family members to join them at Batokunku, especially their wives and children. Some of the household heads reported that, some of their family members are currently seeking refuge in the communities of Gunjur, Sambouya, and Brufut.

•	From the Government, the National Disaster Management Agency (NDMA) is actively supporting the response efforts and has provided the following support so far:
o	Supplied 98 double sized mattresses;
o	40 bags of 50kg rice;
o	10 bags of 50kg sugar;
o	10 gallons of 20L cooking oil;
o	5 bags of onions 
o	Condiments (jumbo, maggi, butter, mayonnaise, tea bags, black pepper)

•	The Gambia Armed Forces (GAF) has provided a tent to be used for additional shelter. Meanwhile, a decision is yet to be reached as to where exactly it can be erected considering the security of the people. 

Additional actions for consideration:
•	Conduct rapid assessment in Gunjur, Sambouya, and Brufut to ascertain the number of people seeking refuge in these communities for necessary humanitarian support.
Since there is no immediate solutions to the problems, we do not foresee the return of these people any time soon as they fear going back to their homes. 

The NS plans to launch a DREF once the trigger is reached.
